I did not try to change my attentiveness because I felt like it gave me more control (even though it really gave me none). The people yelling at us to move around the lasers were really annoying - I figured that I'd be easier to scare if I were focusing on something else, so I didn't listen to them and rationalized that they wouldn't actually hurt us, so it was fine to just walk.
This felt more like an exercise in discomfort. It was all pretty gruesome, but not that frightening.

I know that the goal was to be scary, but I hate loud noises regardless. So I was frustrated by this feature, but there was nothing I could do about it. Instead, I just reminded myself that it would be over soon, and that everything was ok.

These were not so much scary as annoying and unpredictable. I tried to modulate my surprise and not be 'gotten' by them. I did that by listening ahead for the air pump sounds and knowing roughly where they were. It worked some of the time.

I was being extra attentive and looking behind me all the time to make sure I didn't get surprised by anything. That tenseness and attentiveness actually helped, overall. But it was nerve-wracking and scary. In the last section, the girl in front of me did suggest that we all keep a hand on each other's backs so as to stay together and not be as frightened. It helped a little!
We were able to talk in the lines, which really helped manage the fear.

I felt that it was pretty normal to be disgusted by this thing, so I didn't really try to change that. But I found I couldn't NOT pay attention to it. That was strange. It was just such an odd thing to see one of the actors not trying to be super scary, but actually trying to calm something down. It was the most out of place and strange things in the whole event.
This was the one thing I really couldn't avoid or get away from. Instead, we all vocalized how uncomfortable we were to each other, which helped dispel some of the discomfort.
